      <abstract>
        <p id="P2">Genes mutated in congenital malformation syndromes are frequently implicated in oncogenesis<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="R1">1</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="R2">2</xref>, but the causative germline and somatic mutations occur in separate cells at different times of an organismâs life. Here we unify these processes for mutations arising in male germ cells that show a paternal age effect<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="R3">3</xref>. Screening of 30 spermatocytic seminomas<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="R4">4</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="R5">5</xref> for oncogenic mutations in 17 genes identified 2 mutations in <italic>FGFR3</italic> (both 1948A&gt;G encoding K650E, which causes thanatophoric dysplasia in the germline)<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="R6">6</xref> and 5 mutations in <italic>HRAS</italic>. Massively parallel sequencing of sperm DNA showed that the <italic>FGFR3</italic> mutation increases with paternal age, with a similar mutation spectrum at the K650 codon to that in bladder cancer<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="R7">7</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="R8">8</xref>. Most spermatocytic seminomas show increased immunoreactivity for FGFR3 and/or HRAS. We propose that paternal age effect mutations activate a common âselfishâ pathway supporting proliferation in the testis, leading to diverse phenotypes in the next generation including fetal lethality, congenital syndromes and cancer.</p>
      </abstract>
